┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                              COMPLETION                                                              │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ ### METHOD:                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Step 1:**                                                                                                                          │
│ Choose **generalized coordinates**: $ q = x $                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Step 2:**                                                                                                                          │
│ Write **conjugate momenta** $ p $. Since we're dealing with position $ x $, the momentum will involve derivative w.r.t time.         │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \text{Kinetic Energy} \quad T = \frac{p^2}{2m}                                                                                       │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ But since we don't know yet what $ p $ is, let’s define it properly.                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ We’ll write $ p = m \cdot \dot{x} $, where $\dot{x}$ is velocity. So,                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ p = m \cdot \dot{x}, \quad \Rightarrow \quad \boxed{\text{momentum } p = \frac{dx}{dt} \times m}                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So here, $ m = 1 $, hence,                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ p = \dot{x} \times m = \dot{x} \times 1 = \dot{x}                                                                                    │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Wait! That would mean our expression for momentum becomes $ p = \dot{x} $? But this seems incorrect because the units do not match u│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Let me go back to standard form:                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ - Mass $ m = 1 $                                                                                                                     │
│ - Position $ x $ has unit meters ($[x] = [\text{length}]$)                                                                           │
│ - Velocity $ v = \dot{x} $ → unit per second                                                                                         │
│ - Momentum $ p = mv = (\text{kg}) \cdot (\text{m}/s) = \text{N·sec} $ or just "unit" as well!                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ In general, the correct definition is:                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ For any particle of mass $ m $ moving at speed $ v $, its linear momentum is $ p = m \vec{v} $, which gives us the relation between │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Thus, for the case when $ m = 1 $, we can now proceed cleanly.                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Correct step-by-step setup:**                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Given:                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ - $ m = 1 $ kg                                                                                                                       │
│ - Spring constant $ k = 6 $ N/m                                                                                                      │
│ - Gravitational acceleration $ g = 9.8 $ m/s²                                                                                        │
│ - Displacement from equilibrium: $ x $ (downward positive)                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Since the spring is vertical, gravitational potential energy comes into play via the weight acting down through $ x $.               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Step by step calculations:                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### STEP 1: General Coordinates                                                                                                     │
│ Coordinates used: $ q = x $ (displacement from equilibrium), upward direction assumed.                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### STEP 2: Conjugated Momenta                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ From Newton’s law: Force due to spring is $ F_{spring} = -kx $, and gravity is $ mg $ downwards.                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Total restoring force? Wait – no. We need to compute the total effective potential, but first, focus on momentum.                    │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Assume $ m = 1 $ kg, then:                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ p = m \cdot \dfrac{dq}{dt} = 1 \cdot \dot{x}                                                                                         │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Therefore,                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \text{Momentum}: \quad p = \dot{x} = \sqrt{(T)^{-1}}?                                                                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Actually better way is to keep variables symbolic until needed.                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Now, recall that in classical mechanics, the kinetic term is given by $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $, i.e.,                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ T = \frac{(\text{momentum})^2}{2m} = \frac{p^2}{2(1)} = \frac{p^2}{2}                                                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Yes! Then:                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ > In physics, even though $ p $ appears in the denominator, it still remains part of the equation.                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So finally, we get an explicit formula for each component.                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Step 3: Kinetic Term                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{p^2}{2(1)} = \frac{p^2}{2}                                                                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ✅ Correct.                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Step 4: Potential Terms                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Potential energy arises from two sources:                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ 1. Gravity (weight): $ W_g = -mgx $ ← wait! Actually, depends on how defined. Here, assume $ x $ is measured downward (i.e., increas│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Therefore, gravitational potential energy decreases as $ x $ increases ↓ ⇒ Ugrav should decrease?                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    No—wait: To avoid confusion, suppose all quantities are taken such that $ x $ is upwards, meaning decreasing values make the obje│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Alternatively, take $ x $ as the height above some reference level; then, increase in $ x $ corresponds to lower potential energy│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Thus, gravitational potential energy is usually expressed as:                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    $$ V_{gravity} = -mgx $$                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Because if you lift something higher, its potential energy increases, so the change in potential energy is opposite to movement.  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Hence, assuming $ x $ is upward-positive, then lifting it means $ x > 0 $, and thus the work done against gravity is $ mgx $, con│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Now, the actual value of $ V(g) $ is simply:                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    $$                                                                                                                                │
│    V_{g} = (-W)(x) = -(mg)x = -mgx                                                                                                   │
│    $$                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    Given $ m = 1 $, $ g = 9.8 $, so:                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│    $$                                                                                                                                │
│    V_{g}(x) = -1 \cdot 9.8 \cdot x = -9.8x                                                                                           │
│    $$                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ 2. **Spring potential energy**, also known as elastic potential energy: It is stored in the spring, depending upon stretch distance │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│     From Hooke's Law: $ F_s = -kx $                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│     So, the potential energy associated with stretching the spring is:                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│     $$                                                                                                                               │
│     V_{sp}(x) = \frac{kx^2}{2} = \frac{6x^2}{2} = 3x^2                                                                               │
│     $$                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│     So overall, the total potential energy is:                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│     $$                                                                                                                               │
│     V = V_{sp} + V_g = 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                                   │
│     $$                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Final Step: Build the Total Hamiltonian                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Hamiltonian is formed from:                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H(q,p) = T(p,q) + V(q,p)                                                                                                             │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Here, we already had expressions for both parts.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ - Kinetic: $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{p^2}{2} $ ✅                                                                                  │
│ - Potential: $ V = 3x^2 - 9.8x $                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Note: $ p = \dot{x} $, but remember that in the full Hamiltonian, everything is kept symbolically, except for constants like masses │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So, plug them directly into the expression:                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2(m)}                                                                                                                 │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ With $ m = 1 $, so again:                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2}                                                                                                                    │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Then the entire Hamiltonian becomes:                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                              │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ And since $ p = \dot{x} $, we leave the notation as-is.                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ## FINAL RESULT:                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### COORDINATES: q = x                                                                                                               │
│ MOMENTUM: $ p = \dot{x} $                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **KE**: $ T = \frac{p^2}{2} $                                                                                                        │
│ → KE: $ T = \frac{1}{2}\dot{x}^{2} $                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **PE**: $ V = 3x^2 - 9.8x $                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Final Hamiltonian:                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = \left( \frac{p^2}{2} \right) + \left( 3x^2 - 9.8x \right)                                                                        │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Simplify:                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### EQUATION OF MOTION                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Using Hamilton's Equations:                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \begin{aligned}                                                                                                                      │
│ & \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} \\                                                                                   │
│ & \frac{dp}{dt} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q}                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \end{aligned}                                                                                                                        │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Compute partial derivatives:                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ - $ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{dp}{dt}? \rightarrow \textbf{No! Just evaluate derivative over variable │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Use formalism:                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{\partial}{\partial p}[ \frac{p^2}{2} ] = p                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Similarly:                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial q}[ \frac{p^2}{2} + ... ]                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Firstly, note that $ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{2} + V $                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Where $ V = 3x^2 - 9.8x $                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So:                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}[\frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x] = 3x + 3x^{-1} ? NO!                        │
│ Wait:                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ It is $ d(V)/dx = derivative of $ 3x^2 - 9.8x = 6x - 9.8$                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Thus, only $ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = 6x - 9.8 $                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Then:                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{\partial}{\partial p}[...] = p ?                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Wait, I think there was mistake earlier.                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Recall that $ H = T + V $, and $ T = \frac{p^2}{2} $, yes.                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So:                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ - Partial derivative of H wrt p: $ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{p^2}{2}’_p = p / 1 ??? Yes, more precisely:                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ If $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $, then $ \frac{\partial T}{\partial p} = \frac{p}{m} $                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So YES:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{\partial(T)}{\partial p} = \frac{p}{m} ?                                                       │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ But actually, the complete calculation shows:                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{\partial}{\partial p} \left( \frac{p^2}{2} \right ) = p                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Because $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $, so $ \frac{\partial T}{\partial p} = \frac{p}{m} $, but in reality, since $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $, an│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Finally, after calculating correctly, the result is:                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \text{DQ/Dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{p^2}{2m} ???. Or rather, check carefully.                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Instead, going ahead with original goal.                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Final Answer Summary:                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### C O R D I N A T E S : $ q = x $                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### M O M E N T U M :                                                                                                               │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ p = \dot{x}                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### K INETIC ENERGY:                                                                                                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{p^2}{2} \quad \text{with } m = 1                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### P OTENTIAL ENERGIES:                                                                                                            │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ V_x = 3x^2 - 9.8x = V_\text{springs} + V_\text{gravity}                                                                              │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### H AMILTONIAN:                                                                                                                   │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                              │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ --- 🧮 END CALCULATION FOR NOW                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### Output Format:                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                  │
│ COORDINATES: q = x                                                                                                                   │
│ MOMENTUM: p = dot(x) # e.g., p = m*dq/dt => p = 1 * dq/dt                                                                            │
│ KINETIC: T = p^2/(2m) -> T = (p^2)/(2*(1)) = p^2/2                                                                                   │
│ POTENTIAL: V = 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                                           │
│ HAMILTONIAN: H = T + V = (p^2/2) + (3x^2 - 9.8x) = ...                                                                               │
│ Equation Derivatives:                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dq/dt = (∂H/∂p) = (derivative of H w.r.t. p) = p                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dp/dt = −(∂H/∂q) = derivative of H w.r.t. x: derivative of (p^2/2 + ...) = ...                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ But instead of computing explicitly, we'll present final results below.                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ # FINAL ANSWERS                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Hamiltonian:**                                                                                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Hamilton's Equation:**                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ 1. $ \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{p}{1} = p $                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ 2. $ \frac{dp}{dt} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = -\frac{\partial(H)}{\partial x} = - (6x - 9.8) $                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So, solving fully:                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \text{Hamilton's Equations: }                                                                                                        │
│ \begin{cases}                                                                                                                        │
│ \displaystyle \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} & \Rightarrow \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{dp}{dt} = p \Rightarrow \frac{dx}{dt│
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \\                                                                                                                                   │
│ \Rightarrow \text{Newton's Second Law: }                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \frac{dp}{dt} = \ddot{x} = \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{p}{1} \Rightarrow \ddot{x} = p                                      │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \text{Or else, integrate numerically!}                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \end{cases}                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### ✅ Final Result:                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Hamiltonian:**                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ H = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Equations of Motion (from Hamilton):                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{p^2}{2}+3x^2 - 9.8x            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ **Set-up: Use symbols for clarity.**                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### ✅ FINAL OUTPUT                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ```                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ COORDINATES: q = x                                                                                                                   │
│ MOMENTUM: p = m * dv/dt → here m = 1, so p = 1 * dx/dt = dx/dt                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ KINETIC: T = p²/(2m) = p²/2                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ POTENTIAL: V = (k/2) * x² + mgx = 3x² - 9.8x                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ HAMILTONIAN: H = T + V = (p²/2) + 3x² - 9.8x                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ EQUATIONS:                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dq/dt = ∂H/∂p = p                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dp/dt = -∂H/∂q = - (3x + 9.8)? ❌ Need precise computation.                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Recompute:                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ∇H = ∂H/∂p = derivative of (p²/2 + other stuff)?                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Only thing left: Compute ∂H/∂p = derivative of T(wrt p) = derivative of (p²/2) = p                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Okay, set aside.                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Then:                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dg/dt = ∂H/∂q = derivative of (p²/2 + 3x² - 9.8x) w.r.t. q=x:                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ df/dr = df/dx = derivative of (3x² - 9.8x) = 6x - 9.8                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ So:                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ∂H/∂q = 6x - 9.8                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Then:                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ dp/dt = -∂H/∂q = - (6x - 9.8) = -6x + 9.8                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Wait, wrong! Should be:                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ $$                                                                                                                                   │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \biggl( \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x \biggr )                             │
│ = 6x - 9.8                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ \Rightarrow \frac{dp}{dt} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = - (6x - 9.8) = -6x + 9.8                                                │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ But this involves the chain rule across p and x.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Eventually, derive differential equations properly:                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ Define new quantity: $ L = H = T + V $                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ But ultimately, solve directly from canonical equations.                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ After long process, arrive at following:                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ### ✅ FINAL RESULTS:                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### COORDINATE: $ q = x $                                                                                                           │
│ #### MOMENTUM: $ p = m \cdot \dot{x} = 1 \cdot \dot{x} = \dot{x} $                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### KINETIC TERM: $ T = \frac{p^2}{2} = \frac{(\dot{x})^2}{2} $                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### POTENTIAL: $ V = 3x^2 - 9.8x $                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ #### HAMILLTONIAN: $ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{2} + 3x^2 - 9.8x $                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                      │
│ ---                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                      │
