│                                                                COMPLETION                                                                │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ ### **Step-by-Step Derivation**                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### **1. Generalized Coordinates**                                                                                                      │
│ We choose $ q = x $ as the position variable along the horizontal axis.                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### **2. Conjugated Momentum**                                                                                                          │
│ From Newton’s second law:                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{d}{dt}(mv_x) = \textbf{F} = ma = F_{spring}                                                                                        │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Since there is no external force here (only the spring), we can write:                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ a = \ddot{x}, \quad \Rightarrow \quad \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} = F_\text{spring} = -kx                                              │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But let us derive it step by step from the definition of momentum:                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ p = mv = \frac{dp}{dt}? No! Wait!                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let me rederive this properly.                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Correct Definition:**                                                                                                                  │
│ In classical mechanics,                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \dot{q}_i^2 / 2m_i                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wait – correct formula is:                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ For velocity $\dot{q}$,                                                                                                                  │
│ then momentum $p$ is defined via $p = m \cdot v$, where $v = d(q)/dt$                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So given our generalization above:                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Given the mass $m = 5$kg, then:                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ p = m \cdot \dot{x} = 5 \cdot \dot{x} = 5 \cdot \frac{dx}{dt}                                                                            │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Thus, MOMENTUM becomes:                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \boxed{p = 5 \cdot \dot{x}}                                                                                                              │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### **3. Kinetic Energy**                                                                                                               │
│ Using standard expression for KE:                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \frac{(p)^2}{(2m)} = \frac{(5 \dot{x})^2}{2 \times 5} = \frac{25 (\dot{x})^2 }{10} = \frac{5(\dot{x})^2}                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Now plug into T = p²/(2m):                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \left(p^{2}/(2m)\right)                                                                                                              │
│ \rightarrow T = \frac{(p^2)}{2(m)}                                                                                                       │
│ \rightarrow since m = 5 → T = p² / (2×5)                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Yes! So KINETIC ENERGY is:                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{(5 \dot{x})^2}{2 × 5} = \frac{25 \dot{x}^2}{10} = \frac{5 \dot{x}^2}{??                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Actually I need to keep variables symbolic until last moment. But actually, just compute numerically now.                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ If mass is 5 kg, then T = p² / (2m) ⇒ T = p² / (2*(5)) => T = p² / 10 ?                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ No wait! That would make sense only when p has units of kg·rad/s or something else... Actually better way is to define proper expression│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Then again, more precise method comes next...                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### **4. Potential Energy (Spring)**                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ This is due to the spring restoring force acting at distance x.                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Assuming spring stiffness coefficient k = 1 N/m, and assuming the origin is set such that x = 0 corresponds to equilibrium.              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Potential energy associated with spring is:                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ V_S = \frac{k x^2}{2} = \frac{1 x^2}{2}?                                                                                                 │
│ Wait, Spring Force Law says F_spring = -k Δx, which gives U_elastic = ½kΔx²                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So yes: $$ V_spring = \frac{k}{2}\cdot x^2 = \frac{1}{2}x^2 ? Yes!                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Because k = 1 N/m (unit-wise ok).                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So YES:                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ V_{S} = \frac{1}{2}x^2                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Therefore total potential energy is simply:                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ V = V_spring = \frac{1}{2}x^2                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ (Since the question didn't mention any other gravitational effects?)                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Okay assume all is done—so V = ½x²                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### **5. Total Hamiltonian**                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Hamiltonian is sum of kinetic and potential energies:                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ H = T + V = \underbrace{T}_{\frac{p^2}{2m}} + V                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Where T = p²/(2m) ??? Wait, what was original plan:                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Original idea was: "Write kinetic energy T using the letter p."                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ That means even though we used symbol 'mass' earlier, we still leave the term like `p` instead of substituting back-in-mass.             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So take care:                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Mass = 5 kg ✅                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Kinetic Term: T = p² / (2m) ❌ Not yet substituted!                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Instead: Keep it as T = (p²)/(2m) !                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So full T = (p²)/(2m) ! Where m = 5 kg, hence denominator is 10.                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So T = p² / 10 ?                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But hold on: Then why did they say “keep p”? Because in future derivations, e.g., derivative w.r.t time will come up.                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ OK, proceed carefully:                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let’s go through everything once again cleanly.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ## Final Step-by-step Summary                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### Given Data:                                                                                                                          │
│ - Mass $ m = 5 $                                                                                                                         │
