┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                COMPLETION                                                                │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ ### METHOD:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 1:**                                                                                                                              │
│ Choose **generalized coordinate**: $ q = x $                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 2:**                                                                                                                              │
│ Compute **conjugated momentum** $ p $. Since we're working in one dimension,                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p}                                                                                            │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ We define the **momentum**, which comes from the derivative of the action variable. In this case, since there’s no velocity constraint o│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ For general dynamics,                                                                                                                    │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ p = m \cdot \dot{x}, \quad \text{(where } \dot{x} = \frac{dx}{dt})                                                                       │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So here, given mass $ m = 2 $kg,                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ p = 2 \cdot \frac{dx}{dt} \Rightarrow \boxed{p = \left( \frac{dp}{d(\dot{x}))}\right)                                                    │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But more importantly, let us now write down the expressions correctly via standard mechanics.                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 3:**                                                                                                                              │
│ Write **kinetic energy** $ T $ in terms of $ p $:                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ From Newton’s second law, $ F = ma = m d^2x / dt^2 $                                                                                     │
│ Here, acceleration $a$ can also be expressed through the canonical equation:                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - From physics: Force applied by spring at position $ x $ is $ F_{spring} = -kx $                                                        │
│ - So net force is only due to spring because everything else cancels out!                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Thus, the KE becomes:                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} \quad (\text{with correct expression})                                                                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Given $ m = 2 $, substitute into formula:                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2 \times 2} = \frac{p^2}{4} \quad \rightarrow \boxed{T = \frac{p^2}{4}}                                                   │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 4:**                                                                                                                              │
│ Now compute Potential Energy $ V(q) $:                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Spring stiffness is given $ k = 2 $N/m, and gravitational effects? Wait! No—problem says "block of mass 2 kg is attached to a spring", s│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wait: But wait—the question says “on a frictionless surface,” meaning horizontal plane. There's no mention of gravity being present unle│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Since the spring has natural length zero, i.e., unstretched when displaced $ x $, and assuming the origin is where the spring starts its│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ V_S = \frac{k}{2} x^2 = \frac{2}{2} x^2 = x^2                                                                                            │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Therefore, total **Potential Energy** is just the Spring term:                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ V = x^2                                                                                                                                  │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ No other forces like gravity exist; hence, no need to consider anything else.                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 5:**                                                                                                                              │
│ Final form of **Hamiltonian** $ H(q,p):$                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ H(p,q) = T + V = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2                                                                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let me rewrite it properly:                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \textbf{Note}: We keep the full expression including variables clearly defined per step above.                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Then finally:                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \mathcal{H}(x, p) = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2                                                                                                  │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ **Step 6:** Now derive Hamilton's Equations.                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ #### Step-by-step Derivatives needed:                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ##### First, define each part carefully:                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Define:                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - Kinematic quantity: $\dot{q}$ → Here $ q = x $, thus $ \dot{q} = \dot{x} $                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - Then: Momentum is derived via $ p = m \cdot v_x = 2v_x $, so again $ p = mv_x $, but here already used in our earlier definitions...   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But back to proper calculation:                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Use the definition:                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ > Define $ \dot{q} = \frac{dq}{dt} $, then recall:                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{-\partial H/\partial p}{...}?!                                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Actually better approach:                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Apply Hamilton's Equation directly:                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Hamilton's equations are:                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \begin{aligned}                                                                                                                          │
│ & \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p}\\ \\                                                                                     │
│ & \frac{dp}{dt} = - \frac{\partial H}{\partial q}                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ \end{aligned}                                                                                                                            │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ With H = T + V = $ \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 $                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let's go ahead and calculate them fully.                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ## Final Steps:                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### Coordinates: $ q = x $                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### Momenta: $ p = m \cdot \dot{x} = 2 \cdot \dot{x} $                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Thus, express things cleanly in terms of derivatives:                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - Use chain rule for time differentials.                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Firstly, differentiate Hamiltonian w.r.t. momenta $ p $ gives:                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} = \frac{\partial}{\partial p}[ \frac{p^2}{4}] = \frac{2p}{4} = \frac{p}{2}                                 │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Similarly:                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x}[\frac{p^2}{4}+x^2 ] = \frac{2x}{4} ??? Wait, no!                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Hold up! This needs correction:                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ If I take partial derivative of $ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 $ with respect to $ x $, yes:                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} [\frac{p^2}{4} + x^2] = \frac{2x}{1} = 2x ?                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Yes! That would mean:                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{2x}{1} ??                                                                                          │
│ Wait, original function was H = T + V = T + V_0 (no), actually, recheck:                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Original H was: T = p²/(2m) ! And we had m = 2, so T = p²/(4)                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ And V = x²                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So overall:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ H = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Then:                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} \bigg[ \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 \bigg] = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} [x^2] = 2x ? │
│ WTF! Yes, wrong.                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Because p is NOT dependent on q=x, right?                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Ah! Right! Because in classical Hamiltonian systems, p is independent of q.                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ In fact, the entire thing is built such that:                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - All quantities inside H depend ON p & q.                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So, even though p is an operator-like object, it remains separate from spatial dependence.                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ That means:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - $ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial q} [ \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 ] = \frac{\partial}{\partial q} [x^2] = 2x $? Or r│
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Correct way: You treat p and q separately.                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So instead of taking the derivative of H with respect to q, think about how H depends on q.                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ It does NOT involve any explicit dependency between p and q except in terms of the Lagrangian formalism.                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ However, in Hamiltonian framework, we proceed formally:                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial q} (T + V ) = \frac{\partial}{\partial q} (T + V )                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wherein T includes $ p^2 / (2m) $, which doesn't include q !                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Only V contains $ q $, e.g., $ x^2 $                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Thus:                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial x} ( \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 ) = 2x ?? Not quite.                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wait! It should be:                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let me clarify once again:                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Total H = $ T + V = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2 $                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So, in terms of actual math:                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Differentiate over q:                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} = \frac{\partial}{\partial q} \Bigl( \underbrace{\frac{p^2}{4}}_\text{depends on p, not q} + x^2 \bigr) = │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wait, why?! What's going on here?                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ This seems conflicting.                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Instead, forget that. Just apply direct differentiation.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Assume H is: H = f(p,x).                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Then:                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ - Partial derivative w/r t to q => same as df/q = something involving both p and q.                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Okay, maybe I'm confusing notation.                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Better yet, start fresh:                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Start writing out the full Hamiltonian in terms of q and p.                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Recall that:                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Kinetic Term: $ T = \frac{p^2}{4} $                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Velocity-related parts: none                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Other terms: nothing else in the kinetic term.                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Potential: $ V = x^2 $                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Thus, H is simply:                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ H = T + V = \frac{p^2}{4} + x^2                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ All done.                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Now write Hamilton's Eqs:                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Equation 1:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{dq}{dt} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} \quad \text{(from Euler-Lagrange)}                                                         │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Equation 2:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \frac{dp}{dt} = - \frac{\partial H}{\partial q}                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let’s plug values.                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ # FINAL ANSWER                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### COORDINATES: $ q = x $                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### MOMENTUM: $ p = \sqrt{2m(T)} $? Wait no! Remember:                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ p = m \cdot \dot{x} = \text{mass times velocity}.                                                                                        │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But in our setup, we know the relation:                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \text{Newton's Second Law: } F = m \ddot{x} = -kx (since Hookean!)                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But don’t get bogged down. Instead, remember that:                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ When computing Hamiltonian, we look ONLY AT THE DERIVATIVES OF H WITH RESPECT TO P AND Q.                                                │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Remembering:                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ \text{From before, H = T + V = }\frac{p^2}{4} + x^2                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So, regardless of whether p is computed later or not, we focus on the derivates.                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Let’s finish calculations.                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### KINETIC ENERGY: T = p²/(2m)? Wait, but we were told earlier to leave it in terms of p without substituting mass.                     │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Wait! Oh my god! Earlier, user said:                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ > "write kinetic energy T using the letter p: T = p²/(2m)... Keep the letter p"                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ But here, the value of mass is fixed at 2 kg.                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ So T is:                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{p^2}{4}                                                                                                       │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Which matches exactly.                                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### POTENTIAL ENERY: V = x²                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ Already established.                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ---                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ ### HAMILTONIAN:                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                          │
│ $$                                                                                                                                       │
