│ T = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 2 \cdot v^2 = v^2                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But $ v = \dot{x} $, so T = $ \dot{x}^2 $                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But this is wrong.                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Why?                                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Because the momentum is different.                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Wait! Ah! Mistake occurs here:                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Let’s clarify:                                                                                                                            │
│ What defines the **actual** momentum? Is it the **total** amount of energy needed to change the shape of the body?                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Not necessarily equal to $ m \cdot v $, especially when considering non-conservative forces.                                              │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But in classical mechanics, the concept is usually presented as:                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{1}{2} m \cdot \vec{v}^2 = \frac{1}{2} \cdot m \cdot \left( \frac{dq}{dt} \right)^2 = \frac{1}{2} \cdot m \cdot \left( \frac{dq}│
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But in reality, the correct expression is:                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{1}{2} \cdot m \cdot \left( \frac{dq}{dt} \right)^2 = \frac{1}{2} \cdot m \cdot \left( \frac{dq}{dt} \right)^2 = \text{always } │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Wait — nope. Always wrong.                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ At least in this scenario, the correct mathematical structure is:                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{(m \cdot \dot{q})^2}{2m} = \frac{m^2 \cdot \dot{q}^2}{2                                                        │
