│ ---                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ **Step 2:**                                                                                                                               │
│ Write **conjugated momentum**:                                                                                                            │
│ $$ \mathbf{p} = m\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\text{(position)}\right)\quad (\text{here } m = 1) $$                                   │
│ So,                                                                                                                                       │
│ $$ p = \frac{dx}{dt} \cdot m = \frac{dx}{dt} $$                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Wait! Let me correct this step properly.                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Actually, we define **momentum** as derivative of action or canonical momenta.                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Let’s re-derive it correctly!                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ---                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ## Step-by-step Derivation:                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Given:                                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Mass $ m = 1 $ kg                                                                                                                         │
│ Spring stiffness $ k = 1000 $ N/m (i.e., very stiff)                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ We choose **coordinates**, let us take only one dimension to keep things simple: position along x-axis ($ q = x $).                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Then,                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ #### MOMENTUM:                                                                                                                            │
│ From Newton’s second law, Force = ma → F = d(p)/dt? Wait no—correct definition is more like:                                              │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ For motion in classical mechanics, the general form of the Lagrangian method uses velocity-based expressions via $\dot{x}$.               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But here I'll write directly from the standard expression of Momentum:                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ In physics, the **canonical momentum** associated with the variable $ x $ is defined by:                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ \pi_x(x,\dot{x}) = m \cdot \dot{x}                                                                                                        │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Thus, the **velocity-dependent term** becomes part of the total mechanical quantity used in the Legendre transformation.                  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Here, since our goal is just to derive the Hamiltonian, which involves both $ Q $ and its conjugate $ P $. So we proceed carefully now.   │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ---                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ## Corrected Approach:                                                                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Define variables clearly:                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Let $ q = x $ be the spatial coordinate, i.e., displacement along x-direction.                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Let’s denote the speed (derivative w.r.t time):                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $ v_q = \dot{x} $                                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Now compute:                                                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ > **CONJUGATE MOMEANTUM**                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Standard formula:                                                                                                                         │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ p_{(Q)} = \dfrac{dq}{dt} \times m                                                                                                         │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ → But actually better way is through the Lagrange equation.                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Instead, recall that:                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ If $ L(q, \dot{q}, ...) $ is the Lagrangian, then the corresponding "Hamiltonian" can be derived once all quantities are expressed cleanl│
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ However, instead of going into too much detail, go back again quickly.                                                                    │
│                                                                                                                                           │
