│ ### METHOD:                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ #### Step 1: Coordinates                                                                                                                  │
│ We define $ q = x $ as the displacement from equilibrium due to the spring (downward positive).                                           │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ---                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ #### Step 2: Momentum                                                                                                                     │
│ Given $ m = 3 \text{ kg} $                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ \mathbf{v}_x = \frac{\partial}{\partial t}(qx)\quad \Rightarrow \quad p_x = m \cdot \dot{x}                                               │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ So,                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ p = m \cdot \dot{x} = 3 \cdot \dot{x} = 3 \cdot \dot{x}, \quad \text{(mass times derivative)}                                             │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Thus,                                                                                                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ p = 3 \cdot \dot{x} \quad (\text{unit?})                                                                                                  │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ But we keep it symbolic here.                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ ---                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ #### Step 3: Kinetic Energy                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ From classical mechanics,                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 = \frac{1}{2} m(\dot{x}\,\! )^{2} = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot \dot{x} \cdot \dot{x}                                 │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Wait — actually, since $\vec{p}=m \vec{v}$, then $ T = \frac{p^2}{(2m)} $. So let’s write this properly!                                  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \dfrac{p^2}{2m} = \dfrac{(3 \dot{x})^2}{2 \times 3} = \dfrac{9 \dot{x}^2}{6} = \dfrac{3 \dot{x}^2}{2}? Wait no...                     │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Actually better expression:                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Let me do step-by-step again carefully:                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ - Given $ p = m \cdot \dot{x} $                                                                                                           │
│ - Then, $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $? No wait: **kinetic** energy should be $ K = \frac{1}{2}mv^2$, where velocity is derivative of position w.│
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Since $ p = mv $ → $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $? That would make sense only if $ v = \sqrt{p^2 / (2m)) }$ ?                                     │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ No, sorry I'm mixing up definitions now.                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Correct formula is: $$ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} ??                                                                                              │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Wait – Actually, correct definition of KE is:                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ If $ p_i = m \cdot \dot{q}_{i} $, then KE becomes:                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T_{KE} = \sum \frac{1}{2}m(q)^2 = \frac{p^2}{2m} ????                                                                                     │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Yes, because if $ p = m \cdot \dot{q} $, then $ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} $ gives us something like $ T = \frac{1}{2} m \dot{q}^2 $ or similar.  │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ In our case, given $ p = m \cdot \dot{x} $, yes.                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Then, we can compute:                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{p^2}{2m} = \frac{(3 \dot{x})^2}{2 \cdot 3} = \frac{9 \dot{x}^2}{6} = \frac{3 \dot{x}^2}{2}. Yes!                                │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ Final form:                                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                           │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│ T = \frac{3}{2} \dot{x}^2 ?                                                                                                               │
│ $$                                                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                           │
